`crates/ctx-scan` is the standalone CLI crate that maintains a `.context/` mirror of file/directory summaries for an arbitrary tree. Depending on it (as a binary or library) gets you four pipeline entry points ‚Äî scan/check/update/prune ‚Äî plus a `--stop-hook` mode for agent session integration, backed by an integration-test suite that pins their exact contracts.

`src/` and `tests/` are two views of the same pipeline: `src` implements the staged walker‚Üíhash‚Üíreconcile‚Üírunner sequencing and the shared `Staleness` contract that gates model calls, while `tests` enforces that contract from the outside using `FakeFs`/`StubAgent` fixtures plus real-tmpdir runs. Any change to the `Fs`/`Agent` trait signatures in `ctx-summarize` (the dependency both sides wrap) must be updated in the fakes in `tests/reconcile.rs` and `tests/scan.rs` in lockstep with `src/runner.rs`'s real usage.

The crate-wide invariant that matters most to any editor: orphan handling is split by mechanism ‚Äî hash-diff catches deleted leaf files, but directory-subtree deletion is invisible to hash-diff and only caught by `reconcile`'s `find_orphan_artifacts`, and both `src` and `tests` maintain this split independently rather than unifying it. Similarly, non-mutation guarantees (`check_run` read-only, no-agent-call when fresh, `stop_hook` never calling `update_run`) are enforced structurally in `src/runner.rs` and asserted behaviorally in `tests/stop_hook.rs` ‚Äî changing one without the other silently breaks the guarantee. `.ctxignore`-based scope, cwd-relative prompt loading, and the `contract.rs`/CLI-flag mirroring described in `src/rollup.ctx` all apply crate-wide, not just to `src/`.

No intent.md exists to check divergence against.